2025-04-08 21:41 ET - News Release
Mr. Dustin Henderson reports
BLACK MAMMOTH METALS ANNOUNCES COMPLETION OF STRATIGRAPHIC DRILLING AT HAPPY CAT PROPERTY, NV
Black Mammoth Metals Corp. has completed the stratigraphic drilling program at its 100-per-cent-owned Happy Cat property in Lander county, Nevada. 
The program was designed to evaluate various elevated mercury vapour anomalies and geophysical interpretations in an untested area of Tertiary volcanic cover and likely underlying Carlin-style carbonate host lithologies. The stratigraphic drilling guided by the mercury vapour anomalies comprised five reverse circulation holes totalling 1,758 metres. Geochemical results from borehole HC-3 returned 6.1 metres averaging 160 parts per billion gold at 274.32 metres in the overlying volcanic rocks, and HC-3 was testing one of the highest mercury vapour anomalies. All five RC holes intersected limestones and dolomitized mudstones, returning thick intervals up to 70 metres with elevated levels of arsenic, antimony, selenium, molybdenum, cobalt, tungsten, phosphorus and nickel. Selenium values up to 36.6 parts per million were present in the drill samples. High selenium values along with the elevated levels of pathfinder elements suggest a potential Carlin-style gold system nearby or at depth. 
Black Mammoth is currently evaluating the alteration pattern in relation to the identified Carlin-type pathfinder elements, and is considering further geochemical and geophysical surveys (induced polarization) to cover potential target areas.
Prior to the current drill program, an approximately four-square-kilometre area was identified as being hydrothermally altered. Structural modelling suggests the density of the alteration and its density contrast relative to the host rock are typical to those of alteration zones present at other Carlin-type deposits in northern Nevada. The alteration encompasses an area where northerly trending high-angle faults intersect indicated northwest-trending reactivated faults that are known to be of age and orientation as ore-controlling faults occurring at other Carlin-type deposits. Drilling was required to further understand the properties' structure and stratigraphy.
